title.narrative: SUPPLY CHAIN STRENGTHENING

description.narrative: By 2022, national systems for harmonized procurement, logistics and supply chain management are strengthened for equitable and quality Maternal, Neonatal, and Child Health (MNCH), immunization, nutrition and HIV service delivery, which contributes to Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Operations Support To Programme Delivery, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Innovation, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Partnerships And Engagement: Public And Private, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, more children under 5 and women of reproductive age equitably access and utilize evidence-based health, HIV & nutrition interventions, including adoption of key behaviours, especially among vulnerable populations in most deprived states/regions, conflict-affected and peri-urban areas (Goal Area 1 UNICEF Strategic Framework 2018-2021)

title.narrative: By 2022, national systems for harmonized procurement, logistics and supply chain management are strengthened for equitable andquality MNCH, immunization, nutrition and HIV service delivery

description.narrative: Immunization supply chain expansion and strengthening partially resumed in July 2021 in public health facilities and EHOs areas which was temporality suspended following military takeover in February 2021 through technical level engagement with Ministry of Health and partners. The prefabricated cold chain depot in Karen Department of Health & Family Welfare (KDHW) and subdepots in Monywa and Magway were completed, and routine vaccine procurement and supplies re-started as per revised vaccine shipment plan in November 2021. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:17/01/2022
